WRITING.TITLE: The Hidden Blade is Controlled by an Inherited Tendon Instead of the 'String and Ring'
WRITING.TEXT: I've thought about this for many years, before the introduction of the new set of Assassin's Creed came along, but I disagree to what a lot of people imagine as to how the Hidden Blade works. I thought that since all the assassin's are related to the very first assassins, and so in the same way they inherited Eagle Vision, they also inherited a tendon on their fore arms that so that only assassin's can use hidden blades. The tendon would push up against a plate, and once the user stop tensing the tendon, the blade would retract. I understand this probably clashes with when Leonardo looked at the blades in AC 2, and both Altair's and Edwards explanations of the mechanics (which contradict themselves anyway), and also the shift from single to double hidden blades, and there are probably similar contradictions like that. But it would make more sense with in game blue prints of the design, without that 'ring and string' mechanic, as well as making it more of an obvious divide between the assassin's and the rest of humanity.

WRITING.TITLE: Assassin's Creed is an Easy Franchise
WRITING.TEXT: I recently played Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain and initially I thought I would be able to easily go through this 40 hour game. But even in the first chapter I had a very hard time going unnoticed. I will say, I am not good at video games. I often play on easy and I stay away from shooters. Even so, in any Assassin's Creed game, newer or older, I am easily able to comb through the whole stage and take out every enemy and never break my stealth. Also, I can comfortably play Origins and Odyssey on hard, but that's more about their combat. However, when I played Metal Gear, I was completely blind sided from the lack of enemy positioning, and colour contrast for the enemies. Something similar happened with Batman: Arkham Knight, but not to as much of an extent because of all of its other stuff like the vehicle gameplay. I just want to point out that Assassins Creed may be called a stealth series, but it very toned down and basic compared to a lot of other stealth games.

As I've said, I'm not very good at video games. I'm just surprised that I could play this game on Hard while I struggle on other games like Witcher 3 or God of War on Normal. I'll say it again, in not good at video games, and I'm able to admit that. But I still enjoy, like everyone else, all of these amazing masterpieces of incredible design and art.

WRITING.TITLE: My experiences with asking people out
WRITING.TEXT: I've been trying to date around for the last couple of years, and I've asked out 4 girls, the latest one has been my girlfriend for half a year now. And my advice is this; all three other girls that basically said no to my proposal, I'm still good friends with even after they said no. You're relationships with them won't change for the worst if you don't let them. Too many people are afraid of rejection and what it would be like afterwards if they say no. But just take a leap of faith. Sure, if you act hurt and don't talk to them of course your relationship with them will detiorate, you'll just become strangers if you don't try to get back into your previous relationship with them afterwards. I will say, it'll be awkward for a while, but be mature enough and put it past yourselves. From my past experiences, take this mindset with you. Don't hesitate to ask them out because of fear of what will happen if they say no, nobody wants to lose friends, and it's always worth a shot.
